    "slug": "html-dom-fundamentals",
    "title": "HTML DOM Fundamentals",
    "description": "The DOM is the browser's live object tree of an HTML document that JavaScript can read and modify.",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "level": 1,
        "text": "What Is the DOM?"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "When a browser loads an HTML file it parses the markup and builds a " },
          { "value": "Document Object Model", "bold": true },
          { "value": " in memory. The DOM is not the HTML source file. It is a " },
          { "value": "live tree of objects", "bold": true },
          { "value": " where every element, text node, comment, and attribute becomes a JavaScript-accessible object. Changes to the DOM instantly update what the user sees without reloading the page. The DOM standard is maintained by the " },
          { "value": "WHATWG DOM Living Standard", "link": "https://dom.spec.whatwg.org/" },
          { "value": " and documented in full at " },
          { "value": "MDN: Introduction to the DOM", "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Document_Object_Model/Introduction" },
          { "value": "." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "headers": ["Node Type", "nodeType Value", "Example", "Description"],
        "rows": [
          ["Element node", "1", "<p>, <div>, <h1>", "Every HTML element in the document"],
          ["Text node", "3", "Hello World", "The text content inside an element"],
          ["Comment node", "8", "<!-- note -->", "HTML comments in the source"],
          ["Document node", "9", "document", "The root node representing the whole document"],
          ["Attribute node", "2", "class=\"card\"", "Attributes on elements (accessed via element, not tree)"]
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "callout",
        "variant": "info",
        "title": "DOM vs HTML Source",
        "text": "The DOM and the HTML source file are not the same thing. The browser fixes malformed HTML when building the DOM, JavaScript can add nodes that were never in the source, and the DOM reflects the current live state of the page at any moment."
      }
    ],
    "examples": [
      {
        "title": "Exploring the DOM Tree: Parents, Children, and Siblings",
        "description": "This shows how to walk the DOM tree using relationship properties. Each button logs information about the list element's position in the tree — its parent, its children, its siblings, and the difference between childNodes and children.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>DOM Tree Explorer</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <section id=\"team\">\n    <h2>Engineering Team</h2>\n    <ul id=\"member-list\">\n      <li class=\"member\" data-role=\"lead\">Priya Sharma</li>\n      <li class=\"member\" data-role=\"senior\">Rahul Gupta</li>\n      <li class=\"member\" data-role=\"junior\">Anjali Mehta</li>\n    </ul>\n  </section>\n\n  <button id=\"btn-parent\">parentElement</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-children\">children</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-first\">firstElementChild</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-last\">lastElementChild</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-nodes\">childNodes vs children</button>\n\n  <p id=\"output\">Click a button to inspect the DOM tree...</p>\n\n  <script>\n    const list   = document.getElementById('member-list');\n    const output = document.getElementById('output');\n\n    // parentElement: the immediate element parent\n    document.getElementById('btn-parent').onclick = function () {\n      output.textContent = 'parentElement: <' + list.parentElement.tagName.toLowerCase() + ' id=\"' + list.parentElement.id + '\">';\n      // returns <section id=\"team\">\n    };\n\n    // children: HTMLCollection of element children only (no text nodes)\n    document.getElementById('btn-children').onclick = function () {\n      var names = Array.from(list.children).map(function (li) { return li.textContent; });\n      output.textContent = 'children (' + list.children.length + '): ' + names.join(', ');\n    };\n\n    // firstElementChild and lastElementChild skip text/whitespace nodes\n    document.getElementById('btn-first').onclick = function () {\n      output.textContent = 'firstElementChild: \"' + list.firstElementChild.textContent + '\"';\n    };\n\n    document.getElementById('btn-last').onclick = function () {\n      output.textContent = 'lastElementChild: \"' + list.lastElementChild.textContent + '\"';\n    };\n\n    // childNodes includes text/whitespace nodes; children does not\n    document.getElementById('btn-nodes').onclick = function () {\n      output.textContent =\n        'childNodes: ' + list.childNodes.length + ' (includes whitespace text nodes)\\n' +\n        'children:   ' + list.children.length  + ' (element nodes only)';\n      // childNodes will be 7: 3 li elements + 4 whitespace text nodes between them\n    };\n  </script>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
        "output": "The page shows a section with an h2 and three list items, and five buttons. Clicking 'parentElement' shows the section tag. Clicking 'children' lists all three member names. Clicking 'firstElementChild' shows 'Priya Sharma'. Clicking 'childNodes vs children' shows childNodes is 7 (3 elements + 4 whitespace text nodes) while children is only 3.",
        "images": null,
        "video_url": null
      },
      {
        "title": "DOM Selection and Manipulation",
        "description": "This covers the four main selection methods and the most common manipulation operations: reading and writing text, toggling classes, creating new elements, and removing them. These are the building blocks of every interactive component.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>DOM Manipulation</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <h1 id=\"page-title\">Product Catalogue</h1>\n\n  <div id=\"catalogue\">\n    <div id=\"card-1\" class=\"card\" data-product=\"laptop\">\n      <h3 class=\"card-title\">ThinkBook 14</h3>\n      <p class=\"card-price\">Rs 62,000</p>\n    </div>\n    <div id=\"card-2\" class=\"card featured\" data-product=\"phone\">\n      <h3 class=\"card-title\">Pixel 8a</h3>\n      <p class=\"card-price\">Rs 52,999</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <button id=\"btn-read\">Read Content</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-write\">Update Title</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-toggle\">Toggle Featured Class</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-create\">Add Card</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-remove\">Remove Last Card</button>\n  <button id=\"btn-query\">querySelectorAll titles</button>\n\n  <p id=\"log\">Click a button to see the result...</p>\n\n  <script>\n    var catalogue = document.getElementById('catalogue');\n    var log       = document.getElementById('log');\n\n    // getElementById: fastest, by unique ID\n    var card1 = document.getElementById('card-1');\n\n    // querySelector: first CSS match\n    var firstTitle = document.querySelector('.card-title');\n\n    // READ: textContent vs innerHTML\n    document.getElementById('btn-read').onclick = function () {\n      var title = document.getElementById('page-title');\n      log.textContent =\n        'textContent: \"' + title.textContent + '\"' +\n        ' | id attr: \"' + title.getAttribute('id') + '\"' +\n        ' | data-product: \"' + card1.dataset.product + '\"';\n    };\n\n    // WRITE: textContent is safe for user-supplied text\n    document.getElementById('btn-write').onclick = function () {\n      document.getElementById('page-title').textContent = 'Updated Catalogue 2024';\n      log.textContent = 'Title updated via textContent.';\n    };\n\n    // classList.toggle: adds class if absent, removes if present\n    document.getElementById('btn-toggle').onclick = function () {\n      var card2 = document.getElementById('card-2');\n      card2.classList.toggle('featured');\n      log.textContent = 'card-2 classes: ' + card2.className;\n    };\n\n    // createElement + appendChild: create and insert a new node\n    document.getElementById('btn-create').onclick = function () {\n      var newCard = document.createElement('div');\n      newCard.className = 'card';\n      newCard.id = 'card-new';\n\n      var heading = document.createElement('h3');\n      heading.className = 'card-title';\n      heading.textContent = 'Galaxy Tab S9';   // textContent is safe\n\n      var price = document.createElement('p');\n      price.className = 'card-price';\n      price.textContent = 'Rs 74,999';\n\n      newCard.appendChild(heading);\n      newCard.appendChild(price);\n      catalogue.appendChild(newCard);           // insert at end\n      log.textContent = 'Created and appended: ' + newCard.id;\n    };\n\n    // remove(): modern, element removes itself\n    document.getElementById('btn-remove').onclick = function () {\n      var last = catalogue.lastElementChild;\n      if (last) {\n        var id = last.id;\n        last.remove();\n        log.textContent = 'Removed: ' + id;\n      } else {\n        log.textContent = 'No cards left.';\n      }\n    };\n\n    // querySelectorAll: returns static NodeList of all matches\n    document.getElementById('btn-query').onclick = function () {\n      var titles = document.querySelectorAll('#catalogue .card-title');\n      var names  = Array.from(titles).map(function (t) { return t.textContent; });\n      log.textContent = 'Found ' + titles.length + ' titles: ' + names.join(', ');\n    };\n  </script>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
        "output": "The page shows a heading 'Product Catalogue', two product cards with titles and prices, and six buttons. 'Read Content' logs textContent, id attribute, and data-product value. 'Update Title' changes the h1 text. 'Toggle Featured Class' adds and removes the 'featured' class on card-2. 'Add Card' appends a third Galaxy Tab S9 card. 'Remove Last Card' deletes the most recent card. 'querySelectorAll titles' logs all current card title names with a count.",
        "images": null,
        "video_url": null
      }
    ],
    "image_banner_url": null,
    "images": null,
    "video_url": null,
    "when_to_use": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "When " },
          { "value": "reading or modifying page content dynamically", "bold": true },
          { "value": " without a full page reload — the DOM API is the only way to update what users see after the page has loaded." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "When building " },
          { "value": "interactive UI components", "bold": true },
          { "value": " that respond to user actions like clicks, form input, or scroll events." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "When traversing element relationships to find " },
          { "value": "siblings, parents, or children", "bold": true },
          { "value": " — for example, finding the parent form when a submit button is clicked." }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "when_to_avoid": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Avoid frequent individual " },
          { "value": "DOM", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " updates inside loops — batch all insertions using a " },
          { "value": "DocumentFragment", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " and append it once to trigger only a single reflow." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Avoid " },
          { "value": "innerHTML", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " with unsanitised user input — it parses and executes the string as real HTML, creating " },
          { "value": "XSS", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " vulnerabilities. Always use " },
          { "value": "textContent", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " for user-supplied text." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Avoid deep DOM traversal chains like " },
          { "value": "parent.parentElement.children[0]", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " when a simple " },
          { "value": "getElementById", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " or " },
          { "value": "querySelector", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " call would be clearer and less fragile." }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "what_it_solves": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Static HTML alone " },
          { "value": "cannot update content after the page loads", "bold": true },
          { "value": " — without the DOM API every change requires a full page refresh." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Without the DOM, JavaScript has " },
          { "value": "no structured way to find, read, or change page elements", "bold": true },
          { "value": " — it would have no concept of headings, paragraphs, or buttons." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "DOM tree relationships let code " },
          { "value": "navigate complex structures", "bold": true },
          { "value": " without memorising every element ID — for example, finding the parent form of any clicked input." }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "conceptual_understanding": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "The DOM is like a " },
          { "value": "live organisation chart", "bold": true },
          { "value": " for a company. The document is the CEO at the top. Each department is an element node. Each employee is a text or child element node. You can read who reports to whom, move people between departments, hire new employees, or fire existing ones — and the org chart updates instantly to reflect every change." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "The difference between the HTML source and the DOM is like the difference between a " },
          { "value": "blueprint and an actual building", "bold": true },
          { "value": ". The blueprint is the original HTML file — static and unchanging on disk. The building is the DOM — constructed from the blueprint but then modified by workers over time. Renovations happen to the building, not to the blueprint stored in the archive." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "childNodes", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " versus " },
          { "value": "children", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " is like counting " },
          { "value": "everyone in a room versus counting only the adults", "italic": true },
          { "value": ". childNodes includes every node: element nodes, text nodes, and whitespace. children counts only element nodes. The room looks the same but the count depends on who you include in the tally." }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "common_mistakes": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Confusing " },
          { "value": "childNodes", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " with " },
          { "value": "children", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": ": " },
          { "value": "childNodes", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " returns all node types including whitespace text nodes between tags, so its length is almost always higher than " },
          { "value": "children.length", "highlight": true },
          { "value": ". Use " },
          { "value": "children", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " when you only want element nodes." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Using " },
          { "value": "innerHTML", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " with user-supplied data: Setting " },
          { "value": "element.innerHTML = userInput", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " directly injects raw HTML into the page — if the user types " },
          { "value": "<script>", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " or event handler attributes like " },
          { "value": "onerror=alert(1)", "highlight": true },
          { "value": ", the browser executes them. Always use " },
          { "value": "textContent", "bold": true },
          { "value": " for user-supplied text and reserve innerHTML only for trusted, controlled content." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Querying the DOM before it is ready: Running " },
          { "value": "getElementById", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " or " },
          { "value": "querySelector", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " at the top of a " },
          { "value": "<script>", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " tag placed in " },
          { "value": "<head>", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " without " },
          { "value": "defer", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " returns " },
          { "value": "null", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " because the HTML below it has not been parsed yet. Place scripts at the end of " },
          { "value": "<body>", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " or use the " },
          { "value": "defer", "bold": true },
          { "value": " attribute to ensure the DOM is fully built before your code runs." }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "bonus_tips": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "Use " },
          { "value": "document.querySelector", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " with any valid CSS selector to select elements with the same syntax you already know from CSS. For example: " },
          { "value": "document.querySelector('section#team li.member[data-role=\"lead\"]')", "highlight": true },
          { "value": " finds the lead member inside the team section in one call — often more readable than chaining multiple traversal steps." }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": [
          { "value": "When appending multiple new elements in a loop, use a " },
          { "value": "DocumentFragment", "bold": true, "highlight": true },
          { "value": " to batch all insertions into a single DOM update. Create it with " },
          { "value": "document.createDocumentFragment()", "highlight": true },
          { "value": ", append all new nodes to it, then append the fragment to the DOM once. This triggers only one reflow instead of one per element — significantly improving performance for large lists." }
        ]
      }
    ],
